<div id="review_3224056023" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3224056023" />
    <a title="Nick Munene" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/90921615-nick-munene"><img alt="Nick Munene" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1627009789p2/90921615.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3224056023?book_show_action=true">Mar 09, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Nick Munene" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Nick Munene" href="/user/show/90921615-nick-munene">Nick Munene</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3224056023" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17838010625323512061">I enjoyed reading this novel but the first few chapters felt like they needed one more careful edit before publishing. However, the narrative pulled me in especially the struggles in the mines and both grandfathers. I liked Calum best and reread the first few chapters just to get a glimpse of him again and I feel like despite his many shortcomings, life dealt him unfair cards. My best moments were always Grandpa&apos;s drunken musings and the phalic imagery that followed. <br/><br/>In today&apos;s campaigns for min</span>
  <span id="freeText17838010625323512061" style="display:none">I enjoyed reading this novel but the first few chapters felt like they needed one more careful edit before publishing. However, the narrative pulled me in especially the struggles in the mines and both grandfathers. I liked Calum best and reread the first few chapters just to get a glimpse of him again and I feel like despite his many shortcomings, life dealt him unfair cards. My best moments were always Grandpa's drunken musings and the phalic imagery that followed. <br /><br />In today's campaigns for minority empowerment and talks around straight, white man privilege, this book portrays clearly how this sort of characterization is not shared across the board; it's a preserve for the very wealthy straight white men. Switch up the Scottish last names for a minority's last name and the devastating realities of the downtrodden are clearly shown; that they transcend even race and ethnicity. So, in the same ships that brought enterprising Scottish merchants to the New World who made a fortune in the fur trade and the Hudson's Bay Company, others ended up poor up to their next generations with little prospects for advancement due to the labour exploitation of mining companies like Renco Development. No wonder things turned out the way they did for poor Calum who is now an alcoholic excon struggling in Toronto! <br /><br />The tension between French Canadians and other Canadians is poignantly captured when their draft dodger cousin from SF compares them to Mexicans insisting that they should only speak in English since they're in North America. How ridiculous! <br /><br />This is a great piece which needed more polishing up before presentation. I've read that MacLeod was a perfectionist who wrote sentence after sentence as they came to him without altering previous phrases. Hopefully in my next great short stories beinge, I'll remember to sample a few of his especially if he draws forth the tremendous beauty of Cape Breton.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17838010625323512061" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


